# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1780-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was held in Massachusetts on September 4, 1780.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1780-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election] John Hancock, the former delegate to the Continental Congress from Massachusetts, defeated James Bowdoin, the former president of the Massachusetts Constitutional Convention.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1780-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election] The election took place against the backdrop of the American Revolutionary War, in which Hancock briefly participated as a major general of the Massachusetts militia.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1780-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election] Hancock became the first governor elected under the Constitution of Massachusetts, ratified only the previous June; prior to the election, the Massachusetts Governor's Council administered the government following the removal of the last royal governor.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1785-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was held in Massachusetts on April 4, 1785.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1785-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election] The election was decided by the Massachusetts General Court, which elected Bowdoin by a vote of 18 to 10 in the Senate.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1787-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was held in Massachusetts on April 2, 1787.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1787-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election] John Hancock, who had served as the first governor of the Commonwealth of Massachusetts from 1780 to 1785, defeated James Bowdoin, the incumbent governor.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1787-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election] The election took place in the aftermath of Shays's Rebellion, for which Bowdoin was sharply censured.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1787-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election] First elected in 1785, Bowdoin once in office pursued an economic policy of austerity that dramatically increased the tax burden on lower-class citizens, leading to judicial foreclosures against those owing back taxes, including many Continental Army veterans.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1787-massachusetts-senate-election] Elections to the Massachusetts Senate were held during 1787 to elect 40 State Senators.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1787-massachusetts-senate-election] Candidates were elected at the county level, with some counties electing multiple Senators.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1787-massachusetts-senate-election] For election, a candidate needed the support of a majority of those voting.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1787-massachusetts-senate-election] If a seat remained vacant because no candidate received such majority, the Massachusetts General Court was empowered to fill it by a majority vote of its members.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1787-massachusetts-senate-election] The primary issue in this race was the ongoing ratification of the United States Constitution by a separate ratifying convention; the reaction divided the state (and nation) between Federalists and Anti-Federalists, though the factions did not appear as strictly formal political parties until 1789.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1787-massachusetts-senate-election] The elections were also held during the midst of Shays' Rebellion, an armed uprising in Western Massachusetts against the national government, formed in opposition to the ongoing debt crisis.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1787-massachusetts-senate-election] Because Mayhew failed to achieve a majority, the election was put to the General Court, which certified his election with near unanimity.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1787-massachusetts-senate-election] Dalton, Choate, and Greenleaf would subsequently be elected by the General Court.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1787-massachusetts-senate-election] Hastings, Smead, and Phelps were subsequently elected by the General Court.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1787-massachusetts-senate-election] Based on returns from Weston, Ezra Sergant, Abraham Fuller, James Prescot, Joseph Curtis, Thomas Fairweather, Joseph Roberts, John Brooks, and Abner Sanderson also received votes, but how many they received county-wide is unknown.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1787-massachusetts-senate-election] Hosmer and MacFarland were subsequently elected by the General Court.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1787-massachusetts-senate-election] Turner and Cushing were subsequently elected by the General Court.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1787-massachusetts-senate-election] Austin and Dunbar were subsequently elected by the General Court.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1787-massachusetts-senate-election] Cutts and Jordan were subsequently elected by the General Court.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was held in Massachusetts on April 7, 1788.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election] John Hancock, the incumbent governor, defeated Elbridge Gerry, a former delegate to the United States Constitutional Convention.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election] The election took place in the immediate aftermath of a narrow vote to ratify the United States Constitution, which Hancock supported and Gerry opposed.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election] In recognition of his importance to the pro-ratification cause, the "friends of the Constitution" decided to promote the popular Hancock as the Federalists' candidate for governor; meanwhile, Gerry was put forward by the Anti-Federalists who remained skeptical of the incoming federal government.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election] Gerry had been a delegate to the Constitutional Convention in Philadelphia, but refused to sign the final document in protest of the Three-Fifths Clause, which inflated the representation of the slave states in the United States House of Representatives, and the lack of a bill of rights.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election] Although Gerry publicly accepted the outcome of the ratification vote, the issue of the Constitution loomed large in the gubernatorial campaign.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election] Despite the significant opposition to ratification, Gerry was ultimately unable to overcome Hancock's immense personal popularity and was defeated by more than 12,000 votes.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] Elections to the Massachusetts Senate were held in 1788 to elect 40 State Senators.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] If a seat remained vacant because no candidate received such a majority, the Massachusetts General Court was empowered to fill it by a majority vote of its members.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] Exact totals for Smith, the incumbent Senator, are unknown.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] William Williams, Ebenezer Pierce, John Bacon, and William Walker also received votes, though exact totals are unknown.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] Dwight was subsequently elected by the General Court.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] Thomas Durfee, Walter Spooner, and Elisha May also received votes, but their exact totals are unknown.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] Exact totals for the Anti-Federalist ticket were not listed.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] Unaffiliated candidates Peter Coffin and John Choate also received votes, but their exact totals are unknown.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] Jonathan Greenleaf was subsequently elected by the General Court.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] Incumbent Senator David Smead was not re-elected, and his exact vote total is unknown.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] Bliss and Sexton were subsequently elected by the General Court.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] Waterman Thomas, Daniel Cony, and Henry Dearborn also received votes, but their exact totals are unknown.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] Since no candidate received a majority of votes cast, the General Court elected **Dummer Sewall** to the seat.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] Exact totals for Anti-Federalist ticket are not listed.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] Nathaniel Gorham, William Hunt, John Brooks (Federalist), William Hull, Joseph Curtis, James Winthrop and Elbridge Gerry also received votes, though their exact totals are unknown.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] Isaac Winslow, Hugh Orr, Joseph Bryant, James Briggs, and Ebenezer White also received votes.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] Nathaniel Low also received votes, but his exact total is unknown.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-massachusetts-senate-election] Edward Cutts and Nathaniel Wells were subsequently elected by the General Court.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] The **1788–1789 United States Senate elections** were the first U.S.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] Senate elections following the adoption of the Constitution of the United States.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] They coincided with the election of George Washington as the first president of the United States.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] As these elections were prior to the ratification of the Seventeenth Amendment in 1913, senators were chosen by state legislatures.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1788 and 1789.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] Pennsylvania was the first state to select its senators on September 30, 1788, and South Carolina was the last state on January 22, 1789.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] New York, North Carolina, and Rhode Island elected their senators between July 16, 1789, and June 12, 1790, after the convening of Congress.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] Among the original 13 states, ten of them selected their senators prior to the official start of the 1st United States Congress on March 4, 1789, ranging from Pennsylvania in September 1788 to South Carolina in January 1789.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] New York failed to elect its senators until July 1789.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] North Carolina and Rhode Island did not ratify the Constitution until after the 1st Congress began; North Carolina then elected its senators in November 1789, but Rhode Island failed to ratify the Constitution until 1790.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] Under Article I, Section 3, Clause 2 of the U.S.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] Constitution, the actual division of the Senate's seats into the three classes was not performed until after the 1st Congress convened.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] Thus, the 20 elected senators from the ten initial states did not know ahead of time whether they would serve Class 1's interim two-year term, Class 2's interim four-year term, or the full six-year term of Class 3.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] Then starting with New York, a random draw determined which classes each new state's seats would belong to while keeping the three classes as close to the same size as possible.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] Among the initial 20 senators elected before the 1st Congress began on March 4, 1789, 13 of them were Pro-Administration.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] New York failed to elect its senators until after the Congress began, so its seats are labelled here as "Vacant." North Carolina and Rhode Island did not ratify the Constitution until after the Congress began, so their seats are not included here.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] Article I, Section 3, Clause 2 of the U.S.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] The allocation of the classes by lot then took place in May 1789, two months after the first Congress began in March 1789.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] New York was then the first to be treated as a "new state admitted to the Union" under this process when they elected their senators in July 1789, drawing lots to determine which classes their seats would belong to while keeping the three classes as close to the same size as possible.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] In these general elections, the winners were elected in advance of March 4, 1789, the date set to be the beginning of the 1st Congress.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] Ordered by state, then by the class that they were eventually assigned in May 1789.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] In these general elections, the winners were elected in 1789 after March 4; ordered by election date.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] The Maryland General Assembly convened on December 10, 1788, in order to vote for the inaugural holders of Maryland's seats.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] There were two candidates for each seat, and all four were of the Federalist Party.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] An outright majority (50% plus one) was required for a candidate to win.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] Charles Carroll won election over Uriah Forrest by a margin of 3.70%, or 3 votes, for one of the seats.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] This election was decided on the third ballot, after the first did not produce a majority and the second had both candidates tie.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] John Henry won election over George Gale by a margin of 2.44%, or 2 votes, for the other seat.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] This election was decided on the second ballot, after both candidates tied with pluralities on the first.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] In May 1789, the lot draw performed by the 1st U.S.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] Senate assigned Carroll's seat to Class 1, whose term would expire March 3, 1791, and Henry's seat to Class 3, whose term would expire March 3, 1795.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] It was the first such election, and before the actual election the New York State Legislature had to establish rules for proceeding.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] They decided to ballot separately, and then pass a joint resolution once they had concurred in the election of two candidates.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] On July 15, Schuyler was nominated first, and members of each chamber attempted to substitute the names of other candidates, including Ezra L'Hommedieu and Rufus King.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] These motions failed, and Schuyler was elected by a vote of 37 to 19 in the Assembly, and 13 to 6 in the Senate.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] King's election came after individual legislators and the two chambers failed to agree on the election of James Duane, Ezra L'Hommedieu, or Lewis Morris.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] King was then elected unanimously by the Assembly, and by a vote of 11 to 8 in the Senate.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] On July 16, Schuyler and King were appointed to the U.S.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] Senate by a joint resolution of the State Legislature.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] King took his seat on July 25, and drew the lot for Class 3, his term expiring on March 3, 1795.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] Schuyler took his seat on July 27, and drew the lot for Class 1, his term expiring on March 3, 1791.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] The 1st United States Congress convened at New York City, as did the regular session of the New York State Legislature in January 1790.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] Schuyler retained his seat in the State Senate while serving concurrently in the U.S.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] Schuyler was also elected on January 15 a member of the State's Council of Appointments which consisted of the Governor of New York, and four State Senators elected annually by the State Assembly.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] On January 27, the New York State Legislature resolved that it was "incompatible with the U.S.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] Constitution for any person holding an office under the United States government at the same time to have a seat in the Legislature of this State", and that if a member of the State Legislature was elected or appointed to a federal office, the seat should be declared vacant upon acceptance.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] Senator Schuyler, Federal Judge James Duane and Congressmen John Hathorn and John Laurance vacated their seats in the State Senate.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] On April 3, John Cantine, a member of the Council of Appointments, raised the question if Schuyler, after vacating his State Senate seat, was still a member of the council.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] Philip Livingston, another member, held that once elected a member could not be expelled in any case.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] On April 5, Governor Clinton asked the State Assembly for a decision, but the latter refused to do so, arguing that it was a question of law, which could be pursued in the courts.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] Schuyler thus kept his seat in the Council of Appointments until the end of the term.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] North Carolina was the 12th state to ratify the new United States Constitution, doing so in November 1789, months after the First Congress had first convened.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] A few days after that ratification, on November 26, 1789, the two houses of the state legislature jointly elected incumbent Governor Samuel Johnston (who was considered pro-Administration) as North Carolina's first United States Senator.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] The minutes of the state Senate indicate that the two houses had actually voted for both U.S.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] Senate seats, but that no candidate received a majority for the second seat.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] Days later, the state Senate sent messages to the state House of Commons nominating candidates for the state's other Senate seat.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] These included William Lenoir, William Blount, Benjamin Hawkins, and Timothy Bloodworth.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] Hawkins (who was also pro-Administration at the time) was elected jointly by the two houses on December 8, 1789.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] The election was held on September 30, 1788.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] The Pennsylvania General Assembly, consisting of the House of Representatives and the Senate, elected Pennsylvania's first two United States senators, William Maclay and Robert Morris.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-massachusetts] Anti-Federalist William Maclay was elected to the two-year staggered term of the Class 1 seat, while Federalist and founding father Robert Morris was elected to the full six-year term of the Class 3 seat.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election] The **1828 Massachusetts gubernatorial election** was held on April 7.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election] Governor Levi Lincoln Jr., an Adams supporter, was re-elected to a fourth term in office over Democrat Marcus Morton, of the Jacksonian faction.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election] Morton carried only eighteen towns, all of them rural with the exception of Charlestown.
[src:1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election/1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election] The others were Adams, Cheshire, New Ashford, Alford, Tyringham, Montgomery, Westfield, Southwick, Holland, Dana, Charlton, Oxford, Sutton, Seekonk, Berkley, Freetown, and Woburn.
